There is a fourth copy. Somewhere in a dark closet I think I actually have an unopened review unit of OS/2 for the Mach 20, which I kept because I suspected it was the worst-seller in MS history. I also have an original IBM PC with a Mach 20 board installed, along with a Plus HardCard--20 MB! Many moons ago, I briefly resuscitated the HardCard with a hard whack to a wall (stiction?). Additional whacks...Read moreThere is a fourth copy. Somewhere in a dark closet I think I actually have an unopened review unit of OS/2 for the Mach 20, which I kept because I suspected it was the worst-seller in MS history. I also have an original IBM PC with a Mach 20 board installed, along with a Plus HardCard–20 MB! Many moons ago, I briefly resuscitated the HardCard with a hard whack to a wall (stiction?). Additional whacks were unsuccessful, so it no longer boots the system. But last I tried, a bootable floppy would do it–via the Mach 20’s floppy daughterboard.
In answer to Drew, the modem was outboard, 1200 or eventually 2400 bps, and generally attached via the RS-232 port that was more or less standard on multifunction memory cards. IBM’s official solution that nobody bought was a pricey RS-232-only card that wasted one of those precious five slots.
So the final five-slot roster in my original IBM PC was:
1. Mach 20 w/Disk Plus diskette interface
2. Hercules Monochrome Graphics Card
3. Plus 20 MB HardCard
4. Memory expansion card (AST SixPakPlus?) with RS-232 port and parallel port, and about 640K of RAM–and an all-important battery-run clock so you didn’t have to reset the time and date every time you booted up.
5. A mouse port? Maybe an internal modem that I used as a phone dialer with HotLine software? I will have to dig further into the closet, passing the PCjr and Tandy Model 100 (booted last I tried but has a Y2K problem) layers on my way.
BTW, I actually wrote about OS/2 for the Mach 20:
https://books.google.com/books?id=x1yigTsvZxsC&pg=RA1-PA85&dq=stephen+manes+mach+20&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiSp-rbx5j8AhUBIzQIHfzrBEgQ6AF6BAgCEAI#v=onepage&q=stephen%20manes%20mach%2020&f=false
Didn’t seem to help sales much.
